    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-03-14T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-03-14T00:00:00-05:00" n="579"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d579">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/965.</note>
                <head>[Translation.]</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Embassy of Mexico</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-03-14">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 14, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 1053.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Excellency</hi>: Under instructions from my Government I
                    have the honor to address these presents to your excellency to express the
                    pleasure with which it has received the gracious explanations of the President
                    of the United States concerning the mobilization of American troops.</p>
                <p>Mexico could not look for any other attitude on the part of a country which for
                    many years has proved itself so good a friend of hers and has so effectively
                    contributed to her economic development.</p>
                <p>President Taft’s words will no doubt ease public opinion in Mexico, and to that
                    end it has been arranged to insert the message in the newspapers of the
                    capital.</p>
                <p>I beg [etc.],</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">F. L. de la Barra.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
